description: Sukjeongmun Gate, built in the 5th year of King Taejo (1396), is one of the four major gates in Korea - Sukjeongmun Gate, South Gate, East Gate and West Gate, and is called the North Gate. Sujingmun is located in the north of Seoul, with Gyeongbokgung as the center, and Changuimun (Zixiamun) on the right side, like two wings. If people move here, the dragon veins may be damaged, and the country may be in crisis, so in the 13th year of King Taejong (1413), the pine trees were planted and the passage was prohibited. After that, Sujingmun was used as a walking path, and it became a restricted area following the North Korean armed intrusion incident in 1968. In April 2006, the government planned to open the city of Seoul around Beiyueshan, so Sujingmen reopened. In April 2007, Beiyueshan was opened again, and it was divided into 3 visiting routes. Bukaksan Mountain, which has been closed to traffic for many years, has a well-preserved natural environment, and the panoramic view of Seoul can be seen from the mountain.

description: Starting from an elegant French restaurant in 1996, it is a Korean-style hot pot restaurant, a very beautiful barbecue garden restaurant in the world, a design space that nourishes life - Provence Life Pavilion, a sweet and fragrant space Herb Pavilion and a visual space Pop Pavilion. , European-style bakeries and coffee shops and other themed villages. The Provencal village unites stores with their own business ideas in separate buildings. A pottery workshop that designs and manufactures tableware used in restaurants and cafes in Provencal villages; a living hall that sells decorative goods for the design of Provencal villages, mainly hand-painted pottery; making orthodox European-style bakeries that customers like to eat before meals, etc. . In addition, there are pottery shops, flower shops, herb shops, etc. in the Living Hall; while in the Fashion Hall, there are many fashion clothing shops, shoe shops, and decorative boutiques. Each building operates according to different fields, and they are integrated with each other in their own independent operating modes. In addition, in the Herb Garden, a leisure space in Provence, various cultural performances, new experiences, and beautiful events are provided.
